This paper deals with language models, which are typically studied in the field of natural language processing (NLP) and machine learning. Therefore, cs.CL (Computation and Language) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also proposes new architectures for language models, which involves multi-task learning and mixture models, which are common techniques in machine learning. Hence, cs.LG (Machine Learning) is also a likely sub-category. The paper also involves unsupervised techniques for stem identification, which falls under the domain of artificial intelligence (AI), making cs.AI another likely sub-category. The paper also experiments with different architectures for language models, which involves neural networks, making cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper experiments with morphologically complex languages, which may involve computer vision techniques for text processing, making cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) a possible sub-category.
